1.  UseState - 
A.  const [count, setCount] = useState(0); 
    <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Do-Changes</button>
    In this - 
    When we declare top state then on React-Fiber memory our count is created like this - const state = { value : 0 };
    Then when we have called setCount(count + 1) then our Func get called to store/update value of count -> 
    function setState(prevValue){
        state.value = count + 1; 
        //After this change react component re-renders
    }
    By changing state our component our get re-render.
    When we change state at that time new Virtual-dom gets created & it is going compare [ new Virtual DOM vs previous Virtual DOM ] only necessay part gets updated by diff-algorithim-[Finds differences]. 
    React UI updates only when state changes.
    Updating a normal JavaScript variable changes the value in memory, but React does not detect it, so the component does not re-render.
    useState is used to store data that should update the UI.
    Why Normal Variable Doesn't Update UI
    let newData = "Namaste Next-JS";
    Changing this variable:
    newData = "Button Clicked-2";
    Updates value in JavaScript engine
    Console shows updated value
    UI does NOT update because React does not track it.

